Definition: [ἱλαστήριον] neuter of a derivative of {{g2433}}; an expiatory (place or thing), i.e. (concretely) an atoning victim, or (specially) the lid of the Ark (in the Temple)
[ἱλασμός] atonement, i.e. (concretely) an expiator
[Ἰλλυρικόν] neuter of an adjective from a name of uncertain derivation; (the) Illyrican (shore), i.e. (as a name itself) Illyricum, a region of Europe
[ἵλεως] perhaps from the alternate form of {{g138}}; cheerful (as attractive), i.e. propitious; adverbially (by Hebraism) God be gracious!, i.e. (in averting some calamity) far be it
[ἱλαρός] from the same as {{g2436}}; propitious or merry ("hilarious"), i.e. prompt or willing
[Ἰκόνιον] perhaps from {{g1504}}; image-like; Iconium, a place in Asia Minor
[ἱλάσκομαι] middle voice from the same as {{g2436}}; to conciliate, i.e. (transitively) to atone for (sin), or (intransitively) be propitious
[ἱλαρότης] from {{g2431}}; alacrity
[ἱματίζω] from {{g2440}}; to dress
[ἱμάς] perhaps from the same as {{g260}}; a strap, i.e. (specially) the tie (of a sandal) or the lash (of a scourge)
[ἱμάτιον] neuter of a presumed derivative of ennumi (to put on); a dress (inner or outer)
[ἱματισμός] from {{g2439}}; clothing
[ἱμείρομαι] middle voice from ἵμερος (a yearning; of uncertain affinity); to long for
[ἵνα] probably from the same as the former part of {{g1438}} (through the demonstrative idea; compare {{g3588}}); in order that (denoting the purpose or the result) Compare {{g3363}}.
[ἱνατί] from {{g2443}} and {{g5101}}; for what reason ?, i.e. why?
[Ἰόππη] of Hebrew origin ({{h3305}}); Joppe (i.e. Japho), a place in Palestine
[Ἰορδάνης] of Hebrew origin ({{h3383}}); the Jordanes (i.e. Jarden), a river of Palestine
[ἰός] perhaps from εἶμι (to go) or ἵημι (to send); rust (as if emitted by metals); also venom (as emitted by serpents)
[Ἰουδά] of Hebrew origin ({{h3063}} or perhaps {{h3194}}); Judah (i.e. Jehudah or Juttah), a part of (or place in) Palestine
[Ἰουδαία] feminine of {{g2453}} (with {{g1093}} implied); the Judæan land (i.e. Judæa), a region of Palestine
[ἱκανότης] from {{g2425}}; ability
[ἱκανόω] from {{g2425}}; to enable, i.e. qualify
[Ἰησοῦς] of Hebrew origin ({{h3091}}); Jesus (i.e. Jehoshua), the name of our Lord and two (three) other Israelites
[ἱκανός] from ἵκω (ἱκάνω or ἱκνέομαι, akin to {{g2240}}) (to arrive); competent (as if coming in season), i.e. ample (in amount) or fit (in character)
[Ἰεφθάε] of Hebrew origin ({{h3316}}); Jephthaë (i.e. Jiphtach), an Israelite
[Ἰεχονίας] of Hebrew origin ({{h3204}}); Jechonias (i.e. Jekonjah), an Israelite
[ἱερωσύνη] from {{g2413}}; sacredness, i.e. (by implication) the priestly office
[Ἰεσσαί] of Hebrew origin ({{h3448}}); Jessæ (i.e. Jishai), an Israelite
[ἱκετηρία] from a derivative of the base of {{g2425}} (through the idea of approaching for a favor); intreaty
[ἱκμάς] of uncertain affinity; dampness
[ἱερός] of uncertain affinity; sacred
[ἱεροπρεπής] from {{g2413}} and the same as {{g4241}}; reverent
[ἱερόν] neuter of {{g2413}}; a sacred place, i.e. the entire precincts (whereas {{g3485}} denotes the central sanctuary itself) of the Temple (at Jerusalem or elsewhere)
[Ἱεριχώ] of Hebrew origin ({{h3405}}); Jericho, a place in Palestine
[ἱερόσυλος] from {{g2411}} and {{g4813}}; a temple-despoiler
[ἱεροσυλέω] from {{g2417}}; to be a temple-robber (figuratively)
[Ἱεροσολυμίτης] from {{g2414}}; a Hierosolymite, i.e. inhabitant of Hierosolyma
[Ἱεροσόλυμα] of Hebrew origin ({{h3389}}); Hierosolyma (i.e. Jerushalaim), the capitol of Palestine Compare {{g2419}}.
[Ἱερουσαλήμ] of Hebrew origin ({{h3389}}); Hierusalem (i.e. Jerushalem), the capitol of Palestine Compare {{g2414}}.
[ἱερουργέω] from a compound of {{g2411}} and the base of {{g2041}}; to be a temple-worker, i.e. officiate as a priest (figuratively)
[Ἱερεμίας] of Hebrew origin ({{h3414}}); Hieremias (i.e. Jermijah), an Israelite
[ἱερεύς] from {{g2413}}; a priest (literally or figuratively)
[Ἱεράπολις] from {{g2413}} and {{g4172}}; holy city; Hierapolis, a place in Asia Minor
[ἱερατεία] from {{g2407}}; priestliness, i.e. the sacerdotal function
[ἱεράτευμα] from {{g2407}}; the priestly fraternity, i.e. sacerdotal order (figuratively)
[ἱερατεύω] prolongation from {{g2409}}; to be a priest, i.e. perform his functions
[Ἰδουμαία] of Hebrew origin ({{h123}}); Idumæa (i.e. Edom), a region East (and South) of Palestine
[ἱδρώς] a strengthened form of a primary idos (sweat); perspiration
[Ἰεζαβήλ] of Hebrew origin ({{h348}}); Jezabel (i.e. Jezebel), a Tyrian woman (used as a synonym of a termagant or false teacher)
[Ἰωσή] genitive case of {{g2500}}; Jose, an Israelite
[Ἰωσαφάτ] of Hebrew origin ({{h3092}}); Josaphat (i.e. Jehoshaphat), an Israelite
[Ἰωήλ] of Hebrew origin ({{h3100}}); Joel, an Israelite
[Ἰώβ] of Hebrew origin ({{h347}}); Job (i.e. Ijob), a patriarch
[Ἰωάννης] of Hebrew origin ({{h3110}}); Joannes (i.e. Jochanan), the name of four Israelites
[Ἰωαννᾶς] a form of {{g2491}}; Joannas, an Israelite
[Ἰωρείμ] perhaps for {{g2496}}; Jorim, an Israelite
[Ἰωράμ] of Hebrew origin ({{h3141}}); Joram, an Israelite
[Ἰωνᾶς] of Hebrew origin ({{h3124}}); Jonas (i.e. Jonah), the name of two Israelites
[Ἰωνάν] probably for {{g2491}} or {{g2495}}; Jonan, an Israelite
[ἰσχύς] from a derivative of ἰς (force; compare ἔσχον, a form of {{g2192}}); forcefulness (literally or figuratively)
[ἰσχυρός] from {{g2479}}; forcible (literally or figuratively)
[ἰσότης] likeness (in condition or proportion); by implication, equity
[ἴσος] probably from {{g1492}} (through the idea of seeming); similar (in amount and kind)
[ἰσόψυχος] from {{g2470}} and {{g5590}}; of similar spirit
[ἰσότιμος] from {{g2470}} and {{g5092}}; of equal value or honor
[Ἰσραηλίτης] from {{g2474}}; an "Israelite", i.e. descendant of Israel (literally or figuratively)
[Ἰσραήλ] of Hebrew origin ({{h3478}}); Israel (i.e. Jisrael), the adopted name of Jacob, including his descendants (literally or figuratively)
[ἱστορέω] from a derivative of {{g1492}}; to be knowing (learned), i.e. (by implication) to visit for information (interview)

[ἵστημι] a prolonged form of a primary στάω (of the same meaning, and used for it in certain tenses); to stand (transitively or intransitively), used in various applications (literally or figuratively) Compare {{g5087}}.
[Ἰτουραΐα] of Hebrew origin ({{h3195}}); Ituræa (i.e. Jetur), a region of Palestine
[ἰχθύδιον] diminutive from {{g2486}}; a petty fish
[ἰχθύς] of uncertain affinity; a fish
[ἴχνος] from ἰκνέομαι (to arrive; compare {{g2240}}); a track (figuratively)
[ἰσχύω] from {{g2479}}; to have (or exercise) force (literally or figuratively)
[ἴσως] adverb from {{g2470}}; likely, i.e. perhaps
[Ἰταλία] probably of foreign origin; Italia, a region of Europe
[Ἰταλικός] from {{g2482}}; Italic, i.e. belonging to Italia
[Ἰωάθαμ] of Hebrew origin ({{h3147}}); Joatham (i.e. Jotham), an Israelite
[Ἰωάννα] feminine of the same as {{g2491}}; Joanna, a Christian
[ἴσθι] second person imperative present of {{g1510}}; be thou
[Ἰσκαριώτης] of Hebrew origin (probably {{h377}} and {{h7149}}); inhabitant of Kerioth; Iscariotes (i.e. Keriothite), an epithet of Judas the traitor
[Ἰωσῆς] perhaps for {{g2501}}; Joses, the name of two Israelites Compare {{g2499}}.
[ἵππος] of uncertain affinity; a horse
[ἶρις] perhaps from {{g2046}} (as a symbol of the female messenger of the pagan deities); a rainbow ("iris")
[ἱππεύς] from {{g2462}}; an equestrian, i.e. member of a cavalry corps
[ἱππικόν] neuter of a derivative of {{g2462}}; the cavalry force
[Ἰσαχάρ] of Hebrew origin ({{h3485}}); Isachar (i.e. Jissaskar), a son of Jacob (figuratively, his descendant)
[ἴσημι] assumed by some as the base of certain irregular forms of {{g1492}}; to know
[Ἰσαάκ] of Hebrew origin ({{h3327}}); Isaac (i.e. Jitschak), the son of Abraham
[ἰσάγγελος] from {{g2470}} and {{g32}}; like an angel, i.e. angelic
[Ἰούλιος] of Latin origin; Julius, a centurion
[Ἰουλία] feminine of the same as {{g2457}}; Julia, a Christian woman
[Ἰούδας] of Hebrew origin ({{h3063}}); Judas (i.e. Jehudah), the name of ten Israelites; also of the posterity of one of them and its region
[Ἰουδαϊσμός] from {{g2450}}; "Judaism", i.e. the Jewish faith and usages
[Ἰουδαῖος] from {{g2448}} (in the sense of {{g2455}} as a country); Judæan, i.e. belonging to Jehudah
[Ἰουδαϊκῶς] adverb from {{g2451}}; Judaïcally or in a manner resembling a Judæan
[Ἰουδαϊκός] from {{g2453}}; Judaïc, i.e. resembling a Judæan
[Ἰουδαΐζω] from {{g2453}}; to become a Judæan, i.e. "Judaize"
[Ἰοῦστος] of Latin origin ("just"); Justus, the name of three Christian
[Ἰουνιᾶς] of Latin origin; Junias, a Christian
